combinedDonorId
enumValues.description: use this field to filter donor entries by partially matching donorId or submitterDonorId, e.g.: "donor", "donor5"

enumValues.name: coreDataPercentAggregation
enumValues.description:
use this field to filter donor entries by 3 aggregations of submittedCoreDataPercent,
3 enum options to filter by: NO_DATA, COMPLETE, INCOMPLETE.

enumValues.name: dnaTNMatchedPair
enumValues.description:
use this field to filter donor entries by 4 enum values: TUMOR_NORMAL_MATCHED_PAIR, TUMOR_NORMAL_NO_MATCHED_PAIR, NO_DATA.
TUMOR_NORMAL_MATCHED_PAIR = donor has at least 1 tumor/normal matched pair.
TUMOR_NORMAL_NO_MATCHED_PAIR = donor has at least 1 registered tumour or 1 normal DNA sample, but no matched pairs.
NO_DATA = donor has not registered any tumour or normal DNA samples.

enumValues.name: dnaTNRegistered
enumValues.description:
use this field to filter donor entries by 3 enum values: TUMOR_AND_NORMAL, TUMOR_OR_NORMAL, NO_DATA.
TUMOR_AND_NORMAL = donor has at least 1 registered tumour and 1 normal DNA sample.
TUMOR_OR_NORMAL = donor has at least 1 registered tumour or 1 normal DNA sample, but not both.
NO_DATA = donor has not registered any tumour or normal DNA samples.

enumValues.name: mutectStatus
openAccessStatus
rawReads
enumValues.description:
use this field to filter donor entries by 2 enum values: VALID, INVALID.
VALID means the donor has at least 1 submitted tumour/normal sequencing reads.
INVALID means the donor has not registered any tumour or sequencing reads.

enumValues.name: registeredSamplePairs
enumValues.description:
use this field to filter donor entries by 2 enum values: VALID, INVALID.
VALID means the donor has at least 1 registered tumour/normal sample pair.
INVALID means the donor has not registered any tumour or normal samples.

enumValues.name: rnaAlignmentStatus
rnaRawReads
enumValues.description:
use this field to filter donor entries by 2 enum values: DATA_SUBMITTED, NO_DATA.
DATA_SUBMITTED means the donor has at least 1 published tumour or 1 published normal RNA raw reads.
NO_DATA means the donor has no tumour and normal RNA raw reads.

enumValues.name: rnaRegisteredSample
enumValues.description:
use this field to filter donor entries by 2 enum values: DATA_SUBMITTED, NO_DATA.
DATA_SUBMITTED means the donor has at least 1 registered tumour or 1 normal RNA sample.
NO_DATA means the donor has not registered any tumour or normal RNA samples.

fields.name: programDonorPublishedAnalysisByDateRange
fields.description: This query is for finding out how many donors for a given program had data of given types (donorFields) published for the first time before the end of the given date range. The donor count is aggregated into buckets (bucketCount) by date. There must be at least one day per bucket, i.e. the number of days between dateRangeFrom and dateRangeTo must be greater than or equal to bucketCount.

args.name: bucketCount
args.description: bucketCount is used to divide the days between dateRangeFrom and dateRangeTo into date ranges containing at least 1 day each.

args.name: dateRangeFrom
args.description: dateRangeFrom won't appear in the result, unless the days between dateRangeFrom and dateRangeTo are equal to bucketCount. The first date in the result is the last day of the first date range bucket.

types.name: __Directive
types.description:
A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.

types.name: __Field

types.name: __Schema
types.description: A GraphQL Schema defines the capabilities of a GraphQL server. It exposes all available types and directives on the server, as well as the entry points for query, mutation, and subscription operations.

fields.name: types

fields.name: queryType

fields.name: mutationType

fields.name: subscriptionType

types.name: __Type
types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name, description and optional `specifiedByURL`, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.

types.name: __TypeKind
types.description: An enum describing what kind of type a given `__Type` is.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a scalar.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an object. `fields` and `interfaces` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an interface. `fields`, `interfaces`, and `possibleTypes` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a union. `possibleTypes` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an enum. `enumValues` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an input object. `inputFields` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: LIST
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a list. `ofType` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: NON_NULL
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a non-null. `ofType` is a valid field.
